chtext"><div class=3D"w-embed"><center><p>Here's a simple reference for con=
verting between Knots and Miles Per Hour.</p>
<br>
<h3>1 knot is equal to 1.15078 MPH</h3>
<br>
<h3>or</h3>
<br>
<h3>1 MPH =3D 0.868976 knots</h3>
</center></div><p>=E2=80=8D</p><p>=E2=80=8D</p><h3>Knots vs. MPH on the Wat=
er</h3><p>Boaters often encounter two units of measurement when discussing =
speed: miles per hour (MPH) and knots. Both are valid, but the choice depen=
ds on context and purpose.</p><p>=E2=80=8D</p><p>Miles per hour (MPH) is fa=
miliar and intuitive. It=E2=80=99s widely used on land and makes sense for =
casual boating scenarios where precise navigation isn=E2=80=99t critical =
=E2=80=94 such as cruising a lake or sightseeing along the shoreline.</p><p=
>=E2=80=8D</p><p>Knots, on the other hand, are designed for navigation. One=
 knot equals <strong>1.15078 MPH</strong>, but more importantly, it represe=
nts one nautical mile per hour. Since nautical miles align directly with la=
titude, longitude, and marine charts, knots make plotting courses and estim=
ating arrival times simpler and more accurate.</p><h3>=E2=80=8D</h3><h3>Why=
 Knots Remain the Standard</h3><p>Knots are intrinsically tied to nautical =
miles, which correspond with the Earth=E2=80=99s geometry and integrate sea=
mlessly with GPS systems, latitude/longitude coordinates, and traditional p=
aper charts. This is why knots remain the preferred unit for marine navigat=
ion worldwide, regardless of whether a country uses metric or imperial syst=
ems on land.</p><p>=E2=80=8D</p><h3>The Nautical Mile</h3><p>Unlike a statu=
te mile, a nautical mile is derived from the planet itself. One nautical mi=
le equals one minute of latitude, which translates to approximately 6,076 f=
eet or 1,852 meters. This direct relationship between distance and the Eart=
h=E2=80=99s surface made nautical miles the logical choice for navigation, =
allowing distances on charts, marked in degrees and minutes, to correspond =
exactly with real-world travel.</p><p>=E2=80=8D</p><h3>The Origin of the =
=E2=80=9CKnot=E2=80=9D</h3><p>The term =E2=80=9Cknot=E2=80=9D comes from an=
 early, ingenious method of measuring speed at sea. Sailors used a =E2=80=
=9Cchip log=E2=80=9D a weighted wooden board attached to a rope knotted at =
measured intervals. The log was tossed overboard, and as it trailed behind =
the vessel, sailors counted the knots that passed through their hands durin=
g a fixed interval measured by a sandglass.</p><p>=E2=80=8D</p><p>The numbe=
r of knots counted equaled the vessel=E2=80=99s speed in nautical miles per=
 hour.</p><p>=E2=80=8D</p><p>While low-tech by today=E2=80=99s standards, t=
he method was clever, reliable, and effective, even on dark, moonless night=
s when sailors had little more than the wind, stars, and ocean currents to =
guide them.</p><h3>=E2=80=8D</h3><p>=E2=80=8D</p></div></div></div><div cla=
